WEBVTT

00:04.898 --> 00:07.341
Hear God's word from Genesis chapter 45.

00:09.844 --> 00:14.791
Then Joseph could not control himself before all those who stood by him.

00:16.813 --> 00:18.735
He cried, make everyone go out from me.

00:19.296 --> 00:22.440
So no one stayed with him when Joseph made himself known to his brothers.

00:23.061 --> 00:25.124
And he wept aloud, so let the Egyptians heard it.

00:25.945 --> 00:27.406
The household of Pharaoh heard it.

00:28.348 --> 00:30.590
And Joseph said to his brothers, I am Joseph.

00:31.812 --> 00:33.394
It's my father still alive.

00:35.522 --> 00:39.386
But his brothers could not answer him, for they were dismayed at his presence.

00:40.708 --> 00:45.293
So Joseph said to his brothers, come near to me, please, and they came near.

00:46.535 --> 00:54.804
And he said, I am your brother, Joseph, whom you sold into Egypt, and now do not be distressed or angry with yourselves because you sold me here.

00:55.905 --> 00:58.529
For God sent me before you to preserve life.

00:59.970 --> 01:03.314
For the famine has been in the land these two years, and there are yet

01:03.650 --> 01:15.985
five years in which there will be neither plowing nor harvest, and God sent me before you to preserve for you a remnant on earth, and to keep alive for you many survivors.

01:17.266 --> 01:27.058
So it was not you who sent me here, but God has made me a father to Pharaoh and Lord of all his house and ruler over all the land of Egypt,

01:28.034 --> 01:35.042
and go up to my father and say to him, this says, your son, Joseph, God has made me, Lord, of all Egypt, come down to me, do not tear thee.

01:36.344 --> 01:39.748
You shall dwell in the land of Goshen, and you shall be near me.

01:40.308 --> 01:46.536
You and your children and your children's children and your flocks, your herds, and all that you have there I will provide for you.

01:47.637 --> 01:55.506
For there are yet five years of famine to come, so that you and your household and all that you have do not come to poverty.

01:56.738 --> 02:03.206
And now your eyes see in the eyes of my brother Benjamin see that it is my mouth that speaks to you.

02:04.007 --> 02:09.814
You must tell my father of all my honored Egypt and of all that you have seen, hurry and bring my father down here.

02:10.975 --> 02:16.582
Then he fell upon his brother Benjamin's neck and wept and Benjamin wept upon his neck.

02:17.643 --> 02:19.786
And he kissed all his brothers and wept upon them.

02:21.288 --> 02:23.090
After that, his brothers talked with him.

02:25.090 --> 02:32.738
When the report was heard in Pharaoh's house, Joseph's brothers have come, a pleased Pharaoh and his servants.

02:33.659 --> 02:36.362
And Pharaoh said to Joseph, say to your brothers, do this.

02:37.423 --> 02:47.454
Load your beast and go back to the land of Canaan and take your father and your households and come to me and I will give you the best of the land of Egypt and you shall eat the fat of the land.

02:48.415 --> 02:51.538
And you Joseph are commanded to say, do this.

02:52.450 --> 02:58.139
Take wagons from the land of Egypt for your little ones and for your wives and bring your father and come.

02:58.159 --> 03:00.963
Have no concern for your goods.

03:01.945 --> 03:04.689
For the best of all, the land of Egypt is yours."

03:05.911 --> 03:14.484
The sons of Israel did so, and Joseph gave them wagons according to the command of Pharaoh and gave them provisions for the journey to each and all of them.

03:14.544 --> 03:20.914
He gave a change of clothes, but to Benjamin, he gave 300 shekels of silver and five changes of clothes.

03:21.826 --> 03:30.855
To his father, he sent as follows, 10 donkeys loaded with the good things of Egypt, and 10 female donkeys loaded with grain, bread, and provision for his father on the journey.

03:31.695 --> 03:36.600
Then he sent his brothers away, and as they departed, he said to them, do not quarrel on the way.

03:38.362 --> 03:42.425
So they went up out of Egypt, came to the land of Canaan to their father, Jacob.

03:43.326 --> 03:48.051
And they told him, Joseph is still alive, and he is ruler over all the land of Egypt.

03:48.731 --> 03:51.474
And his heart became numb, for he did not believe them.

03:53.314 --> 04:04.272
But when they told him all the words of Joseph, which he had said to them, and when he saw the wagons that Joseph had sent to carry him, the spirit of their father, Jacob, revived.

04:05.554 --> 04:07.317
And Israel said, it is enough.

04:08.399 --> 04:10.322
Joseph, my son, is still alive.

04:10.482 --> 04:12.626
I will go and see him before I die.

04:13.607 --> 04:18.676
The grass weathers and the flowers fade, but the word of our God will stand forever.

04:18.996 --> 04:20.018
And then you may be seated.

04:23.010 --> 04:23.491
Pray with me.

04:30.418 --> 04:33.661
Merciful God, we give you thanks for your word.

04:35.523 --> 04:38.546
Your word which truly stands forever.

04:39.668 --> 04:41.850
Your word which is alive and active.

04:43.251 --> 04:49.618
Your words which cuts through all the layers we try to put between us and your word, and I pray that you would

04:51.202 --> 04:52.905
Speak to us mightily this morning.

04:53.305 --> 05:02.699
Your spirit would apply these words to our lives and give us conviction and strength to carry them out in our daily lives.

05:03.280 --> 05:05.163
We pray this in your holy name, amen.

05:07.166 --> 05:16.499
I remember once growing up, I had a youth pastor who was preaching from the gospels preaching about forgiveness and Jesus's command.

05:16.519 --> 05:19.744
You know, and the disciples come to Jesus and they say, Jesus, how many times we gotta forgive?

05:20.185 --> 05:20.946
You gotta wonder like,

05:21.474 --> 05:24.378
What's the precursor to someone having to ask that kind of questions?

05:24.398 --> 05:25.981
Like, hey, this guy, yeah, I got this uncle.

05:26.802 --> 05:28.264
How many times I really got to forgive them?

05:28.304 --> 05:37.338
And Jesus says this kind of a strange answer, seven times 77, which is not our passage, isn't about that specific passage.

05:37.358 --> 05:39.982
So just take my word for it.

05:40.022 --> 05:41.464
That means you always have to forgive.

05:41.504 --> 05:42.466
Like you can't get out of it.

05:44.409 --> 05:45.571
So you know, you always have to forgive.

05:45.591 --> 05:47.794
When someone asks for forgiveness, you always have to forgive.

05:48.226 --> 05:49.908
And, you know, Youth Pass was teaching about that.

05:49.928 --> 05:51.531
I was like, yeah, that seems to make sense.

05:52.172 --> 05:53.193
Sounds pretty easy.

05:53.213 --> 05:57.660
I can't imagine having an enemy, you know, praying for those who persecute you.

05:57.680 --> 05:58.641
I was like, that sounds easy.

05:59.723 --> 06:01.285
Someone asked me, I have forgiveness is easy.

06:02.406 --> 06:05.932
And I thought it was the easiest thing that God asked me to do.

06:05.972 --> 06:07.614
And then you live a little.

06:08.756 --> 06:10.418
And then you start to get wounded by people.

06:10.882 --> 06:18.171
And it's not just like someone that you don't know that wounds you, it's someone that you know really well, someone that's close to you wounds you, and you experience betrayal.

06:19.672 --> 06:21.454
And that's kind of a different kind of wound.

06:21.514 --> 06:27.021
That's not an easy one to just let go and forgive.

06:27.121 --> 06:31.706
And that's when those commands started to take root in my life.

06:31.726 --> 06:33.669
It's like, well, how do you actually forgive people?

06:34.189 --> 06:38.194
And maybe what puts a little bit of finer point on this

06:38.658 --> 06:41.882
is when you stop and you consider what forgiveness actually means.

06:42.884 --> 06:45.307
Which I don't know, I think we have the sense of what it means to forgive.

06:45.327 --> 06:47.570
Yeah, you kind of let go of someone's offense against you.

06:48.331 --> 06:51.375
But one of my favorite definitions comes from a guy named Tim Keller.

06:51.415 --> 06:52.617
He wrote a book on forgiveness.

06:52.697 --> 06:54.339
It's a book I commend to you.

06:54.820 --> 06:56.562
But he kind of defines it like this.

06:56.622 --> 06:59.306
It's releasing someone of debt that's owed to you.

07:00.067 --> 07:02.790
So someone sins against you that they've incurred a debt.

07:04.112 --> 07:08.658
He says that forgiveness is releasing someone of debt that's owed.

07:09.186 --> 07:11.731
and releasing a right to revenge on that person.

07:13.474 --> 07:20.467
Now, when you consider the definition of forgiveness, something like that, all of a sudden the idea of forgiving somebody is even harder, isn't it?

07:21.428 --> 07:25.616
Especially when someone's wounded you deeply, profound betrayal.

07:27.580 --> 07:31.026
And one of the reasons why it's hard, I've been thinking about this for myself for maybe some

07:31.554 --> 07:32.875
people that are hard for me to forgive.

07:32.915 --> 07:36.539
No one in this room, of course, I'll forgive any of you for any offense very quickly.

07:36.859 --> 07:39.381
It's other people, it's just people out there that you have to worry about.

07:40.723 --> 07:48.850
But when someone wounds you deeply, I think the reason why I hold on and don't want to forgive is that I'm worried, am I just excusing their behavior?

07:50.112 --> 07:53.375
Am I making light of their offense against me by letting it go?

07:53.415 --> 07:55.517
Is this kind of making it cheap?

07:55.537 --> 07:56.598
Am I minimizing it?

07:56.678 --> 08:01.202
Am I saying by letting it go and forgiving that what they did against me is actually

08:01.442 --> 08:02.424
It's just not that big a deal.

08:02.444 --> 08:03.826
I can just let it go.

08:03.866 --> 08:05.269
Don't worry about it.

08:05.749 --> 08:06.731
I think we worry about that.

08:07.733 --> 08:15.005
And I wonder how in the world is that fair, especially when you've been wounded deeply and the betrayal is profound.

08:17.029 --> 08:18.391
So what do we do with that?

08:18.431 --> 08:21.857
Well, we know that we have to forgive because Jesus tells you, you have to forgive.

08:22.078 --> 08:23.901
If you want me to forgive you, you got to forgive others.

08:24.923 --> 08:25.864
And so we go through the motions.

08:25.904 --> 08:26.866
We say the words.

08:27.106 --> 08:27.907
Yes, I forgive you.

08:27.927 --> 08:32.151
It's like, you know, parents, when you got your kids fighting, you pull them together and say, say, I'm sorry, I'm sorry.

08:32.191 --> 08:33.152
Say, I forgive you, I forgive you.

08:33.212 --> 08:33.792
Okay, no hug.

08:33.832 --> 08:35.474
And now you go, okay, be friends.

08:35.514 --> 08:37.936
It's like, well, is that actually happening in that moment?

08:37.976 --> 08:39.638
No, are those words important to say still?

08:39.678 --> 08:41.540
Yes, you should still make your kids say those words.

08:42.221 --> 08:45.283
But you also know the difference between saying something and actually meeting something.

08:46.625 --> 08:47.666
So we say the words.

08:48.607 --> 08:53.752
We say, yeah, of course I forgive that person, but, right, but I still hold this against them.

08:54.492 --> 08:56.274
I still hedge my bets around this person.

08:58.018 --> 08:59.319
We still hold on to it.

08:59.339 --> 09:10.311
We still have a, when someone's name is mentioned that we have an offense with the bitterness creeps up and that bitterness feels good because that person's indebted to us.

09:10.551 --> 09:11.733
We have power over them.

09:11.793 --> 09:18.760
So how can we possibly actually work through this and learn to be a forgiving people?

09:18.800 --> 09:19.541
How can we?

09:20.101 --> 09:24.466
I mean, this is where Joseph's story here in chapter 45 of Genesis is so powerful.

09:26.082 --> 09:27.664
Do you remember Joseph's history, right?

09:27.684 --> 09:29.527
He was sinned against grievously.

09:29.988 --> 09:32.011
He was sold into slavery by his brothers.

09:33.032 --> 09:33.593
Pretty big deal.

09:34.394 --> 09:40.683
And now he's finally in this position to exact his revenge against his brothers.

09:40.703 --> 09:42.326
He's got this power over them.

09:43.728 --> 09:45.991
And he's in a position, he can do whatever he wants to them.

09:46.352 --> 09:48.134
And the Pharaoh won't think twice about it.

09:48.174 --> 09:49.456
He's like, yeah, I guess they deserved it.

09:49.997 --> 09:51.679
He could torture them for the rest of their lives.

09:52.581 --> 09:53.522
And what does he do?

09:54.786 --> 09:56.889
He doesn't seek revenge, he forgives.

09:56.949 --> 10:01.676
Not just forgives, he has restored relationship with them.

10:03.740 --> 10:04.721
It's a powerful scene.

10:04.761 --> 10:11.271
Although the words for goodness and reconciliation are not used at all in this passage, this is what this narrative is showing us.

10:11.331 --> 10:12.353
And that's the beauty of narrative.

10:12.373 --> 10:13.895
It explains and shows us things.

10:14.776 --> 10:17.260
So their word pictures for what forgiveness looks like.

10:17.520 --> 10:21.266
It's one of the most powerful chapters of forgiveness in all of scripture.

10:23.042 --> 10:40.864
And so as we kind of meditate on this theme of forgiveness, there's three aspects of forgiveness I wanna talk about that show us that forgiveness is so important, not just because of like interpersonal relationship issues, but it's bigger than that.

10:41.144 --> 10:49.394
Forgiveness is ultimately about preserving and promoting life and renewal of all things and all creation.

10:51.234 --> 10:53.957
And we see this as we learn these three things about forgiveness this morning.

10:53.977 --> 10:56.521
First, forgiveness requires giving up control.

10:57.922 --> 11:02.468
Second, that forgiveness is only possible by trusting in God's providence.

11:03.409 --> 11:06.653
And finally, that forgiveness opens the door to reconciliation.

11:08.055 --> 11:10.518
So again, forgiveness requires giving up control.

11:10.558 --> 11:15.365
Forgiveness is only possible by trusting God's providence.

11:16.246 --> 11:19.730
And finally, that forgiveness opens the door to reconciliation.

11:21.602 --> 11:27.868
So first, forgiveness requires giving up control.

11:29.409 --> 11:31.591
And for the record, this is probably the easiest of the three things.

11:31.671 --> 11:33.053
So this is a buckle up.

11:33.293 --> 11:34.334
This is a rough one.

11:34.654 --> 11:36.616
If you want to be a forgiving person, it's not easy.

11:37.877 --> 11:39.479
Forgiveness requires giving up control.

11:40.059 --> 11:45.985
So again, in the end to this scene, Joseph, throughout his speech, he reminds them and tells them how powerful he is.

11:46.005 --> 11:48.988
It's almost as if like the Pharaoh works for him.

11:49.028 --> 11:51.570
He's ruler over all the land.

11:51.650 --> 11:56.075
He's a father to Pharaoh, which is kind of a strange saying, we're not gonna get into that, what that means.

11:56.155 --> 12:09.051
But all I have to say is Joseph is a powerful man, ruler of the land, his brothers, he's been testing them and they're caught in his trap and they're exposed and he has all the power in this moment.

12:10.032 --> 12:18.482
And if you think about it, forgiveness, if forgiveness is releasing someone of a debt that's owed to you, that they've incurred,

12:19.970 --> 12:22.093
Then that means you have power over them.

12:22.113 --> 12:24.437
You have control over that person.

12:24.497 --> 12:25.398
That means they owe you.

12:26.520 --> 12:27.281
They have a debt to you.

12:27.321 --> 12:32.729
And what does Joseph do with the debt that they have towards him?

12:34.552 --> 12:35.153
He gives it up.

12:36.275 --> 12:37.056
And you see this here.

12:37.076 --> 12:44.487
It's this powerful scene where he clears the room and says, make everyone go out for me so that no one stayed with him or Joseph made himself known to his brothers.

12:45.168 --> 12:48.914
And he wept aloud so that all the Egyptians heard it and the household of Pharaoh heard it.

12:50.274 --> 12:55.880
He clears the room and you got to think his brothers are like, what is about to happen to us?

12:56.561 --> 12:57.622
And then he starts weeping.

12:58.383 --> 13:03.489
And this isn't just like, you know, a little tear-jurkel end of a Disney movie kind of thing.

13:04.350 --> 13:15.122
This is like loud, uncontrollable, loud weeping, where people in another room could hear him, where his servants could hear him.

13:17.634 --> 13:18.916
This is profound openness.

13:18.936 --> 13:22.141
He's losing control even of his own emotions.

13:22.702 --> 13:23.523
It's not measured.

13:24.024 --> 13:25.065
It's not dignified.

13:25.106 --> 13:29.052
And then he says these words, I'm Joseph.

13:30.914 --> 13:32.176
It's my father's still alive.

13:34.159 --> 13:34.820
I'm Joseph.

13:36.844 --> 13:38.626
He reveals himself to his brothers.

13:39.828 --> 13:43.634
He gives up his control of the situation and tells his brothers

13:43.810 --> 13:44.251
who he is.

13:44.311 --> 13:45.453
This is like one of those scenes.

13:45.493 --> 13:56.530
If you're, you know, you watch that movie when you know something about the character, but as an audience, but the characters don't know that about the person, and finally it's all building up this tension until you get this big reveal.

13:56.590 --> 13:58.873
This is what's happened is this big reveal.

14:00.996 --> 14:02.198
And how do the brothers respond?

14:02.258 --> 14:03.580
It terrifies them.

14:04.923 --> 14:06.665
They were dismayed at his presence.

14:08.788 --> 14:09.810
And then it says this,

14:10.050 --> 14:13.595
So Joseph said that his brothers come near to me, please, and they came near.

14:13.635 --> 14:17.740
And he said, I am your brother Joseph, whom you sold into Egypt.

14:17.760 --> 14:25.291
But now do not be distressed or angry with yourselves because you sold me here, for God sent me before you to preserve life.

14:27.554 --> 14:29.777
So in this moment, Joseph reveals himself.

14:30.077 --> 14:35.845
He draws them close, not to punish them, but he assures them.

14:35.865 --> 14:36.846
He's like, don't worry.

14:36.886 --> 14:39.730
I'm not going to harm you.

14:41.058 --> 14:41.980
He shows mercy.

14:42.020 --> 14:43.863
He still names their wrong.

14:43.883 --> 14:45.265
He's like, you, you did sell me.

14:45.626 --> 14:46.107
Like you did.

14:46.147 --> 14:49.693
Just, you know, I'd remember you didn't sell me in the slavery.

14:49.753 --> 14:52.578
Just so we clear that did happen.

14:53.479 --> 14:55.883
It's real, but he doesn't hold it over him.

14:56.845 --> 14:58.348
He takes that power he has over him.

14:58.929 --> 14:59.550
He names it.

15:00.111 --> 15:00.872
He doesn't pretend.

15:02.074 --> 15:02.895
And let's go of it.

15:03.997 --> 15:06.802
The leverage that he has over them, he gives it up.

15:07.938 --> 15:11.563
And in fact, him giving it up actually gives his whole family leverage in the land.

15:11.603 --> 15:13.786
They get the best of the land because of who they are.

15:13.806 --> 15:18.733
He gives it up.

15:18.753 --> 15:23.159
And for us to be a forgiving people, for us to follow Christ's commands to forgive.

15:25.582 --> 15:33.373
As Christ has forgiven us, it requires us giving up control over people who owe debts to us.

15:35.015 --> 15:37.298
Again, this doesn't mean you ignore the problem.

15:38.466 --> 15:41.951
When God forgives us, He does not ignore the problem of sin in our lives.

15:42.211 --> 15:43.132
Sin is never ignored.

15:43.313 --> 15:44.154
It's always dealt with.

15:44.895 --> 15:46.737
We can be confident to name it because of that.

15:48.980 --> 15:50.542
But what does it do with that wrongdoing?

15:50.602 --> 15:51.684
It forgives.

15:51.804 --> 15:54.788
It gives up that control that you have over someone else.

15:54.848 --> 15:56.651
It releases someone of the debt.

15:56.671 --> 16:08.146
And this is a beautiful thing to think about, especially it's beautiful when this has happened to you and you've done wrongs someone grievously and they have let go of

16:08.322 --> 16:09.384
let you out of that debt.

16:09.444 --> 16:10.806
It feels amazing.

16:11.006 --> 16:14.672
It's a beautiful thing, but it's very dangerous thing too, isn't it?

16:15.853 --> 16:19.839
Giving up the control that you have over someone's debt is hard.

16:21.021 --> 16:23.204
Because again, it can feel like cheap.

16:24.166 --> 16:25.428
It can feel like you're just excusing.

16:25.448 --> 16:27.190
It's like, no, but they owe me.

16:27.471 --> 16:28.492
You don't understand.

16:28.532 --> 16:31.297
They actually owe me right now.

16:32.498 --> 16:36.625
If I do this, I'm not just giving up control, but I'm actually giving them power over me.

16:36.665 --> 16:37.586
Why would I do that?

16:37.954 --> 16:39.356
I need to at least make them earn it.

16:40.357 --> 16:44.122
I need to make, I need them to just show me that they're really actually sorry.

16:46.405 --> 16:46.966
They have to earn it.

16:46.986 --> 16:48.648
They have to pay for it and somehow.

16:48.668 --> 16:53.294
How can we possibly give up that control that we have?

16:55.277 --> 16:57.299
Ultimately, it's because this is what Christ does for you.

16:59.382 --> 17:04.429
Listen, while you were his enemy, while you were in grievous sin against him, what does he do?

17:04.489 --> 17:05.490
He dies for you.

17:06.466 --> 17:13.713
It's not us who first love Christ, but it's Christ who first loves us, releasing us of our debt to Him.

17:13.773 --> 17:16.576
And as He has done that for you, so you were called to do for others.

17:17.657 --> 17:34.034
And unless you actually can release someone of the debt that they owe you, even when they don't ask, and especially when they don't deserve it, I fear it means you will never understand what Christ has actually accomplished for you, the measure with which He's forgiven you.

17:34.818 --> 17:42.408
You know, Jesus tells this great parable of this really wealthy man who has somebody who works for him and he forgives him of a debt.

17:43.189 --> 17:45.932
And then it's a big debt and that guy's like, sweet.

17:45.992 --> 17:51.679
And he goes back to his house and he has got a servant who's owes less to him and he throws him in prison for it.

17:52.600 --> 17:55.544
And then the rich wealthy leader's like, what are you doing?

17:56.886 --> 18:01.472
How could you not forgive this person who owes less when you just received that great forgiveness from me?

18:02.713 --> 18:03.314
And this is what,

18:03.650 --> 18:08.137
we have to be able to see is how much we've been forgiven if we want to be a forgiving people.

18:09.559 --> 18:14.486
We have offended God by our sin far more than anyone has offended us.

18:16.469 --> 18:25.783
As he forgives and releases us of that, so we're called to forgive, and we first are able to forgive by giving up our sense of control of others.

18:30.671 --> 18:31.632
This leads to another question.

18:31.692 --> 18:32.914
How can we possibly

18:33.666 --> 18:35.648
Give up that control what we have over others.

18:35.708 --> 18:40.554
When we give up that control others, it puts that other person in a position where they might be able to harm us again.

18:40.614 --> 18:46.121
How can we possibly put ourselves in that kind of vulnerable position?

18:46.141 --> 18:54.610
I think this is actually a thing that keeps us from moving towards forgiveness because we know what it's going to cost and we don't want to pay that price.

18:55.091 --> 18:57.714
So how do we actually move towards somebody and let go?

19:01.474 --> 19:03.357
This leads to the second thing we learn about forgiveness.

19:03.397 --> 19:08.685
First, forgiveness requires kind of giving up that sense of control over someone that you have as they owe you.

19:09.185 --> 19:14.533
But secondly, forgiveness is only possible by trusting God's providence.

19:15.995 --> 19:19.781
Forgiveness is only possible by trusting God's providence.

19:20.181 --> 19:28.754
Listen, if vulnerability is the cost of forgiveness, which is given up power and control, then providence makes that cost bearable.

19:29.218 --> 19:31.400
And you see this lace throughout this passage.

19:33.743 --> 19:41.932
Verse five, it says, and now do not be distressed or angry with yourselves because you stole me here, for God sent me before you to preserve life.

19:42.033 --> 19:45.396
Verse seven again, and God sent me before you to preserve you.

19:46.097 --> 19:52.424
And then again, in verse eight, so it was not you who sent me here, but God.

19:54.667 --> 19:57.490
Joseph clearly emphasizing this point

19:57.794 --> 20:02.601
that he will emphasize further in Genesis 50 with the more famous line from Joseph.

20:04.845 --> 20:06.587
Listen, this isn't you that sent me here.

20:07.829 --> 20:09.572
This is God that sent me here.

20:11.595 --> 20:13.197
He's making it clear God sent me.

20:14.760 --> 20:17.944
He's not where he is because his brothers sold him ultimately.

20:17.985 --> 20:21.129
He is there because God wants him there.

20:22.752 --> 20:26.898
This is not God merely making the best out of a bad situation.

20:27.906 --> 20:43.761
This is not God just using something, trouble something's like, oh, the brothers show them, okay, now I can work this out and make him still get to Egypt, I got this plan, I got this plan, BAC, turn that page 24 or whatever in a binder to see what's next for him, this is not what's happening here.

20:44.622 --> 20:53.530
Clear in this language, in this language throughout Joseph's story, as God is not just using this, but he's causing this all to happen, he's sending him.

20:55.192 --> 20:57.874
It's this word that we use is providence, which is,

20:58.402 --> 21:01.445
God's governing all creatures and their actions.

21:02.687 --> 21:06.191
God's providence has led Joseph to Egypt.

21:06.912 --> 21:10.916
And when we talk about God's providence, especially in situations like that, it does open up a can of worms.

21:10.976 --> 21:23.410
If you want a fuller conversation of providence, and the first chapter where we meet Joseph, I did a whole sermon, was on the providence of God speaking about this story.

21:24.162 --> 21:29.829
But just to get in this a little bit, because this is the whole point of this second point, is God's providence helping us in forgiveness.

21:30.990 --> 21:33.693
The question and the can of worms around this topic is always this.

21:34.654 --> 21:43.304
If God is actually governing all creatures in their actions, and that includes the actions that are sinful, so does that mean God caused the brothers to sin?

21:43.344 --> 21:51.954
I mean, this is God's doing, and God's actually moving this is, how can you and I be responsible for sin if God's the one that's actually governing

21:52.162 --> 21:53.084
every one of our actions.

21:53.344 --> 21:55.207
Doesn't that mean God's responsible for sin?

21:56.069 --> 21:58.853
And there's always this tension in this paradox about Scripture.

21:58.873 --> 22:02.539
And these two things are to be held together and they are both true.

22:03.240 --> 22:06.686
Because it's largely left unexplained for us in the deepest level that we want.

22:06.786 --> 22:09.892
We want everything to be neat and tidy so we can understand everything.

22:10.332 --> 22:13.978
But when it comes to the things of God, there are just things that we will not fully understand.

22:14.018 --> 22:18.546
And what Scripture does not apologize for the fact that God is sovereign over all things.

22:19.490 --> 22:24.336
He's providentially leading things into your life and leading you out of those things to better things.

22:24.376 --> 22:25.818
He is in control of every situation.

22:25.838 --> 22:29.162
Nothing happens outside his divine control and his plan for your life.

22:29.242 --> 22:34.789
And yet, you and I are still responsible for our sin, for our actions.

22:34.849 --> 22:36.091
God is not the author of sin.

22:36.191 --> 22:38.253
He is full of righteousness and holiness.

22:38.334 --> 22:39.896
These things are true.

22:39.936 --> 22:42.739
God's plan was to move Joseph to Egypt.

22:44.201 --> 22:46.704
And yet he is not responsible for the sin of these brothers.

22:47.225 --> 22:48.306
There's a paradox there.

22:49.762 --> 22:51.805
And I'm not sure we will fully solve this.

22:51.945 --> 22:53.947
On this side of eternity, it is a mystery.

22:54.648 --> 23:07.805
And the key for this mystery here for us is this, that forgiveness does not require us to solve that mystery, but it requires us to trust that our God is in control, that is providentially in control, governing all the creatures and their actions.

23:09.167 --> 23:13.152
And what that means for us is that we need to trust that God is the one that's writing our story.

23:15.235 --> 23:17.778
It's not those who sin against you that are writing your story,

23:18.050 --> 23:19.933
It's not your bitterness that is right in your story.

23:19.953 --> 23:21.515
It is God is right in your story.

23:21.916 --> 23:26.864
And even the hard stuff that he brings into your life, even the offenses that he brings into your life, he will lead you through them.

23:27.965 --> 23:31.391
Your life is not happening to you by accident, by chance.

23:32.272 --> 23:34.616
God is never surprised by your life.

23:35.357 --> 23:38.442
Even the challenges that come, God's never like, oh, we didn't see that coming.

23:39.704 --> 23:42.268
It's not, it's not who God is.

23:42.348 --> 23:46.354
Our God's character is sovereign, divinely,

23:46.466 --> 23:48.489
seeing everything that happens in this world.

23:50.392 --> 23:53.738
And I think this perspective helps change how we see forgiveness.

23:53.898 --> 23:59.467
Because if God is writing Joseph's story, then his brothers aren't the authors of his future.

24:00.369 --> 24:09.864
Their actions wound him and put him in a tough spot for 20 years before he finally gets to have this position here in Egypt, but they don't define him.

24:10.184 --> 24:11.186
They don't control him.

24:12.898 --> 24:15.662
So he doesn't have to hold on to these things that have been done to them.

24:15.702 --> 24:21.592
He doesn't need the exact vengeance on his brothers, but he can trust the God in his time and we'll take care of these things.

24:22.353 --> 24:27.561
He can let go of any obsession that he has of control because he knows he actually doesn't have control.

24:28.503 --> 24:35.614
Anytime we think we're in control of this situation, you're not, you're actually not in control as much as you think.

24:35.654 --> 24:40.402
As someone who loves, I love to have control over things, right?

24:41.410 --> 24:42.872
I have to just remind it for myself.

24:42.932 --> 24:44.434
I'm not in control of anything.

24:47.418 --> 24:49.761
And this is what providence helps teach us.

24:50.943 --> 24:52.685
That God's the one that's actually in control.

24:52.725 --> 25:00.315
God's the one that's writing the stories of our lives and this frees you if it frees myself, it frees Joseph from having to play God.

25:01.337 --> 25:05.462
From trying to figure out like I need to control all the outcomes of the story.

25:07.525 --> 25:08.466
You can forgive.

25:09.986 --> 25:12.009
You can let go of outcomes.

25:12.049 --> 25:16.156
You can release someone of the debt they owe you even when it is great.

25:17.538 --> 25:23.568
When you learn how to trust that God is providentially writing your story.

25:25.451 --> 25:28.996
Now you might think, well, I wish you would have written my story a little different.

25:29.637 --> 25:33.283
I can think of some parts I might want to like erase and change a little bit.

25:34.225 --> 25:35.026
How is this?

25:35.298 --> 25:36.019
How is this good?

25:36.079 --> 25:40.483
How can I trust Him when He's bringing so much pain into my life?

25:42.045 --> 25:44.567
Because of where your life will ultimately be led to.

25:45.488 --> 25:46.049
And it's life.

25:46.129 --> 25:51.014
You see this here, like the reason for preservation in verse five, God sent me before you to preserve life.

25:51.474 --> 25:57.300
And again in verse seven, God sent me before you to preserve for you a remnant on earth to keep you alive.

25:59.522 --> 26:03.506
God's providence always moves us towards life.

26:04.482 --> 26:05.484
This is his character.

26:06.625 --> 26:09.350
The pain and suffering that come into our lives are not our end.

26:10.031 --> 26:13.296
In the moment you think it is, in the moment you think this season is going to last forever.

26:13.336 --> 26:14.478
This is pain is forever.

26:15.960 --> 26:17.583
But it's not the promise of Scripture.

26:17.603 --> 26:19.206
This is teaching us about his character.

26:21.169 --> 26:22.230
I've got to lead you to life.

26:24.374 --> 26:27.559
Now, sometimes we get the experience, taste of that life on this side of eternity.

26:27.599 --> 26:29.522
Sometimes we don't get to taste it until

26:31.202 --> 26:35.307
our eternal life until we taste death and then we get to experience life everlasting.

26:35.367 --> 26:43.856
Either way, God is leading you to life and you can further you can trust that he is leading you to life because our God is a God who entered our story.

26:46.599 --> 26:51.505
Our God is a God who entered the pains of what it means to be human.

26:51.525 --> 26:53.687
He took our debt and our pain on himself.

26:54.869 --> 26:59.794
The cost of this was his own death, but his life did not end in death.

27:00.354 --> 27:01.576
But he rose to new life.

27:03.238 --> 27:05.542
This gives us a cycle of what he's doing in this world.

27:05.602 --> 27:09.228
He's bringing all creation through death and rebirth.

27:11.211 --> 27:16.419
Because he's doing this in the world and because he insert himself into the story, he's not aloof from your pain.

27:16.499 --> 27:17.400
He knows your pain.

27:17.420 --> 27:18.322
He knows your suffering.

27:18.342 --> 27:20.104
He knows betrayal.

27:21.366 --> 27:26.354
As a human, he knows betrayal from Judas and the Romans who killed him.

27:27.586 --> 27:30.972
As God, he knows betrayal from his people that are constantly rebelling against him.

27:31.012 --> 27:32.254
He knows betrayal.

27:33.376 --> 27:34.438
He knows your pains.

27:34.818 --> 27:36.942
He knows the harms that you've happened to you.

27:37.563 --> 27:41.490
And he is the only one that can lead you through those pains and those deaths to life.

27:41.570 --> 27:42.912
And he promises to do that.

27:45.717 --> 27:49.443
We're just called to trust that that is where he is taking us.

27:49.463 --> 27:50.105
Listen, I get it.

27:50.145 --> 27:53.330
People have harmed you in grievous ways and ways that I don't know.

27:55.170 --> 27:57.653
And it's hard to trust that God is in control of situations.

27:57.693 --> 28:03.119
And this story is showing us, listen, God is not surprised by the pains in your life.

28:03.159 --> 28:06.062
He brings us into our life to bring us out, to bring us to life.

28:07.604 --> 28:09.946
We can trust Him with our story.

28:11.548 --> 28:14.251
Because He knows our story because He has tasted our story.

28:15.653 --> 28:24.082
And when we learn to trust God with our story, trust that He is in providentially guiding all of our aspects of our lives

28:25.218 --> 28:27.541
It's not just forgiveness that becomes possible.

28:29.324 --> 28:33.089
But resurrection on this side of eternity becomes possible.

28:33.489 --> 28:35.973
Reconciliation becomes possible.

28:37.255 --> 28:42.822
This is the third thing we see here is that forgiveness opens the door to reconciliation.

28:44.825 --> 28:46.588
So we think about forgiveness.

28:46.628 --> 28:50.373
Forgiveness is this release of debt where forgiveness releases debt.

28:51.514 --> 28:54.098
Reconciliation restores relationship.

28:54.754 --> 29:01.364
Well, he could release someone of a debt that they owe to you and still never talk to them again and not become best friends again.

29:03.567 --> 29:06.591
But reconciliation does the second half of that.

29:06.631 --> 29:10.657
Forgiveness releases that reconciliation, restored relationship, friendship, fellowship.

29:11.138 --> 29:12.359
And you see this in the scene here.

29:13.601 --> 29:17.026
Not only is there forgiveness that's happening, but there's reconciliation.

29:17.727 --> 29:18.428
There's weeping.

29:18.909 --> 29:19.750
They're embracing.

29:20.151 --> 29:20.832
They're kissing.

29:20.872 --> 29:22.514
And at the end,

29:22.594 --> 29:24.377
After that, his brothers talked with him.

29:24.417 --> 29:28.224
I love that it's like telling us, yeah, they had a conversation.

29:28.244 --> 29:30.367
It was kind of fun to think about.

29:30.387 --> 29:31.970
They're catching up over the last 20 years.

29:31.990 --> 29:32.591
What's going on?

29:33.753 --> 29:35.677
I'm kind of curious what they talked about.

29:35.697 --> 29:37.420
There's a lot of interesting things that that could have gone.

29:37.460 --> 29:41.426
But there's peace, there's reconciliation with him and his brothers.

29:42.027 --> 29:44.311
And then you get this profound moment at the end.

29:45.473 --> 29:48.178
Verse 25 to 28, it says, so they went up

29:48.290 --> 29:57.001
out of Egypt and came to the land of Canaan to their father Jacob, and they told him Joseph is still alive, his ruler over all the land of Egypt, and his heart became numb, for he did not believe him.

29:57.822 --> 30:07.874
And when they told him all the words Joseph, which he had said to them, which he had saw the wagons that Joseph had sent to carry him, the spirit of their father Jacob revived, and Israel said it is enough.

30:08.154 --> 30:09.836
Joseph, my son, is still alive.

30:09.876 --> 30:12.259
I will go see him before I die."

30:12.680 --> 30:16.344
This is a beautiful moment.

30:16.364 --> 30:18.066
This father who lost his son,

30:19.938 --> 30:25.164
who before said, I'm going to go down to Sheol in mourning, go into death mourning.

30:25.205 --> 30:29.490
He finds out his son is alive.

30:31.853 --> 30:35.758
I know we struggle at doing this, especially in stories that we know well.

30:35.798 --> 30:40.724
Just imagine you spent 22 years thinking a child of yours is dead.

30:43.067 --> 30:46.451
And to find out that there's still life, even if you don't have children in this room, you can imagine.

30:47.172 --> 30:49.074
So that's an overwhelming feeling.

30:50.530 --> 30:52.733
22 years, you thought your son was dead.

30:53.374 --> 30:54.555
Not only that, it's your favorite son.

30:55.276 --> 30:56.358
I mean, I don't have favorite sons.

30:56.398 --> 30:57.359
You guys are all the same.

30:57.459 --> 30:58.280
To me and my eyes.

30:59.882 --> 31:01.004
But it's his favorite son.

31:01.024 --> 31:05.930
I thought he was dead and now he's alive.

31:07.132 --> 31:14.241
It's an overwhelmingly beautiful scene and there's this other aspect to it that's hinted at here but is not explicit.

31:14.802 --> 31:15.983
Like the truth is coming out.

31:16.063 --> 31:18.066
Lies are being revealed in this moment.

31:18.306 --> 31:18.566
Right.

31:18.606 --> 31:20.730
The fathers, I mean, they've got a long journey to Egypt.

31:20.770 --> 31:25.117
The fathers are going to be like, so what happened when you got the cloak?

31:25.137 --> 31:29.203
Did you really see them eaten alive by an animal or what happened there?

31:29.464 --> 31:30.465
You know, they're going to have to tell them.

31:31.287 --> 31:33.150
And you actually get a hint to this in verse 24.

31:33.210 --> 31:35.053
It says, do not quarrel on the way.

31:35.774 --> 31:36.475
What is that about?

31:37.536 --> 31:41.042
Well, most commentators would suggest that that's probably like, hey,

31:41.346 --> 31:45.432
Don't like trying to figure out how you're going to sell the story to your dad when you get there.

31:45.472 --> 31:48.656
I know you guys are going to try to work something out to make it sound like it's not your fault.

31:48.736 --> 31:50.138
No, it's all right.

31:50.799 --> 31:51.320
It's all good.

31:51.380 --> 31:51.961
I forgive you.

31:52.421 --> 31:53.222
You can be honest with him.

31:54.804 --> 31:57.288
I mean, my dad's getting his son back.

31:57.308 --> 31:58.510
I think he'll let this go.

31:58.530 --> 32:04.658
But there's this beautiful moment where this family, there's been through so much chaos.

32:05.794 --> 32:09.498
So much weirdness, so much disobedience, so many gross stories even.

32:09.518 --> 32:18.868
This family is finally being restored, and the Father's spirit is revived from shield to life, and there's this resurrection moment in this family.

32:19.749 --> 32:21.210
I think that's what reconciliation is.

32:21.290 --> 32:23.973
It's resurrection moments, from death to life.

32:24.994 --> 32:27.717
This is where forgiveness doesn't just release guilt.

32:27.757 --> 32:32.562
It creates an opportunity for life, and then they get this

32:32.706 --> 32:52.106
They get a new land and then there's reunited family and this is a new remnant that preserves this line that even Jesus himself comes from the line of Judah, resurrecting that which is lost and it makes it possible for reconciliation to happen and just restore this healed relationship.

32:52.166 --> 32:52.787
It's beautiful.

32:54.869 --> 32:59.954
And this is where forgiveness leads us to wholeness, to life.

33:00.770 --> 33:07.420
not just in a personal life, but life that explodes out into the world, that touches everything that we touch.

33:09.062 --> 33:12.728
This is this beautiful moment where you see that love and it's keeping no record of wrongs.

33:12.768 --> 33:14.510
It doesn't pretend like sin didn't happen.

33:14.991 --> 33:24.405
It's not like it's against putting parameters in place to help us not sin again, but it enables people to live together without the past controlling the present.

33:24.425 --> 33:25.266
It's a beautiful moment.

33:29.090 --> 33:38.862
One of the things about this point that I'm trying to make clear too, is that forgiveness opens the door to reconciliation, but forgiveness is not guaranteed reconciliation.

33:41.125 --> 33:43.788
There's not going to guarantee this part, and many of you have tasted this.

33:45.550 --> 33:47.653
Forgiveness is something that you're commanded to do.

33:48.534 --> 33:56.964
It's a non-optional part of, not that we don't struggle, I'm not saying you have to be perfect at this, but forgiveness is something that we are called to do.

33:57.144 --> 33:58.546
It's a command of the Lord.

33:59.042 --> 34:00.564
Forgive as I've forgiven you.

34:00.924 --> 34:03.127
And this is something we're all fight and work to grow.

34:03.187 --> 34:04.088
Yes, I need to forgive.

34:05.209 --> 34:07.111
Reconciliation is not a command.

34:07.431 --> 34:08.312
It's not guaranteed.

34:08.973 --> 34:14.820
As part of our ministry, the ministry of reconciliation, the service of reconciliation where we restore all things to crisis.

34:15.120 --> 34:18.344
So what we're working for is not guaranteed.

34:20.206 --> 34:27.474
There's a lot of situations where reconciliation, where restored friendship and fellowship is just not always possible.

34:29.218 --> 34:42.800
in cases of profound abuse and domestic violence, sexual abuse, reconciled relationships with those people is not always possible or recommended this side of eternity.

34:44.543 --> 34:53.458
It doesn't mean that like sometimes you can have a someone who has faith in Christ commit a grievous sin against someone else and there can be forgiveness.

34:53.890 --> 34:59.560
And maybe you'll run into that person one day in heaven and that's a reconciled moment where you can, you can do that in heaven.

35:00.141 --> 35:05.090
But sometimes this side of eternity, those, those relationships don't heal in that kind of way.

35:07.394 --> 35:09.297
And this is not a failure of faith.

35:10.680 --> 35:14.226
This is the reality of living in a world that is still very much broken.

35:15.746 --> 35:19.530
a world that is still in the midst of this death and resurrection cycle.

35:19.570 --> 35:22.133
We're still going through many cycles of death and resurrection.

35:22.153 --> 35:33.426
Every time you die in your own life and you live to Christ, part of the old man dies and you rise again with less of the old man than you have before, but we have to go through cycles of this over and over.

35:33.466 --> 35:38.411
Just like you and I are going through this, you and your relationships are going through these death resurrection cycles.

35:38.672 --> 35:44.338
The whole world is going through this death and resurrection cycle, which means there's still much that needs to be burned off of this world.

35:44.418 --> 35:46.000
That's not gonna last for eternity.

35:46.661 --> 35:49.645
Which means we still live in a broken world.

35:51.668 --> 35:52.929
Which makes it challenging for us.

35:54.872 --> 35:56.314
How do we live with some ambiguity?

35:57.596 --> 36:05.086
The big question that you wanna know is, well how do we know if this is a reconciliation situation or if I can just forgive but not reconcile?

36:05.166 --> 36:07.289
I'd really rather not reconcile with this person.

36:08.250 --> 36:09.972
So this is probably not a reconciled situation.

36:09.992 --> 36:12.135
I'm just gonna forgive him and I'm gonna ignore him for the rest of my life.

36:12.175 --> 36:12.596
Sound good?

36:12.756 --> 36:14.258
All right, let's go.

36:14.594 --> 36:17.277
That's what you want to know is like, how do I know about my situation?

36:18.338 --> 36:20.641
And this is where, again, there's a lot of gray here.

36:20.681 --> 36:27.229
It requires so much humility, like honest humility to look first at the gospel, say, okay, I've been forgiven much.

36:27.289 --> 36:28.611
I'm called to forgive much.

36:29.812 --> 36:33.516
Start there, the humility to recognize that and the wisdom to apply it in life.

36:33.576 --> 36:35.519
And how do we have humility and wisdom?

36:35.559 --> 36:41.746
Well, I think ultimately we gain those things and are able to apply those to our lives in the context of community.

36:42.530 --> 36:46.576
with churches for to help us grow in humility and wisdom.

36:46.616 --> 36:54.647
And in the church, we learned to help discern this for each other because sometimes you just need time before you can move towards reconciliation.

36:54.707 --> 36:58.232
Sometimes you do need to stop at forgiveness.

36:58.252 --> 36:59.313
I'm going to release you that's dead.

36:59.353 --> 37:02.377
I'm actually going to fight towards not being bitter.

37:02.417 --> 37:04.420
I'm going to release this, let go of bitterness.

37:06.002 --> 37:11.570
My challenge to you is don't be quick to assume your situation is a non-reconcilating situation.

37:13.314 --> 37:23.265
I mean, just because it's hard and challenging and just because you can't imagine how it could happen doesn't mean that God's not leading you to make that happen or to work towards it and to fight for it.

37:24.106 --> 37:31.073
I mean, I can't imagine it was easy for Joseph again, his brother sold him into slavery.

37:31.093 --> 37:33.355
It's kind of a big deal.

37:33.956 --> 37:34.677
And yeah, here he is.

37:35.658 --> 37:39.602
I mean, if someone, if you had siblings sell you into slavery,

37:39.970 --> 37:44.436
I'm guessing it would be hard for you to imagine actually being friends with them again, right?

37:46.438 --> 37:48.340
But that's what happened to Joseph.

37:49.642 --> 37:52.245
I can't imagine I was easy to forgive, to let go of it.

37:52.646 --> 37:53.847
His wounds were not small.

37:56.030 --> 38:05.341
All to say is be slow to assume your situation is a non-reconcilating type of situation, especially when you consider the character of our God.

38:06.663 --> 38:09.106
Our God is a God who brings dead things to life.

38:12.674 --> 38:14.136
That's just specialty.

38:15.018 --> 38:16.781
I mean, that's how creation started.

38:17.422 --> 38:19.144
The cosmos was dead, right?

38:19.164 --> 38:19.765
It was void.

38:20.607 --> 38:21.969
He burrs it with life.

38:22.009 --> 38:26.957
Even in exile, God creates life.

38:27.958 --> 38:29.080
He feeds His people.

38:30.823 --> 38:35.250
He goes into the grave and comes out again three days later.

38:36.354 --> 38:38.136
And his resurrection bears fruit.

38:38.376 --> 38:41.219
I mean, the fruits of the spirit, that's what your lives, they produce fruit.

38:41.239 --> 38:43.681
Our God is a fruitful, multiplying God.

38:43.741 --> 38:45.543
He brings life from death.

38:45.563 --> 38:53.031
So if you're going to assume anything, assume that God wants to bring life out of your broken relationships.

38:54.312 --> 38:57.035
And assume that he is the one God who can.

38:58.716 --> 38:59.157
And he can.

38:59.217 --> 39:04.402
There's so many stories I could tell you of marriages who

39:04.514 --> 39:08.079
There's no, if you looked at it from the outside, you're like, oh, that's not gonna end well.

39:09.280 --> 39:13.906
And they fight and they have life or betrayals from friendships.

39:16.509 --> 39:18.632
Our God is a God who resurrects things.

39:19.833 --> 39:21.415
Miracles happen by his hand.

39:23.738 --> 39:26.222
This is what we're called to believe in, to have faith in, to work towards.

39:26.342 --> 39:29.746
Of course, if someone, if the offending party or whatever,

39:30.050 --> 39:31.832
doesn't want to work towards reconciliation.

39:31.852 --> 39:34.474
That doesn't really happen, but the Lord changes hearts.

39:37.317 --> 39:40.621
This is meant to define us to be forgiving, reconciled people.

39:40.681 --> 39:46.286
Again, this is what we read earlier, that we have a ministry of reconciliation.

39:46.326 --> 39:57.938
This is how we serve in the world as we bring renewal to be a people who have a short memory of wrong, to be a people who are quick to forgive because we know that we have

39:58.722 --> 40:01.185
been transformed by a God who first forgave us.

40:02.466 --> 40:08.693
And we are called to live out in this world as a people not ruled by bitterness, but ruled by love, by mercy, by grace.

40:09.934 --> 40:19.044
And as we receive this, we go out into the world with this, into our homes, into our families, into our neighborhoods, into our workplaces as forgiven and forgiving people.

40:22.408 --> 40:27.794
And this makes you a life-giving person, because forgiveness always leads to life.

40:28.546 --> 40:39.358
And in a world and in a city that is desperate for life, we're called to be people who bring this ministry of reconciliation that leads to life to bear.

40:41.039 --> 40:48.928
May we become and grow into this kind of people who bring the ministry of reconciliation to bear in a world that's war with itself.

40:49.929 --> 40:50.390
Pray with me.

40:52.372 --> 40:58.258
Merciful God in heaven, we give you thanks for your word, your word which you tell us is better than life,

41:00.386 --> 41:06.713
I pray that you would help us to see exactly what you've forgiven us from.

41:08.815 --> 41:16.204
As we see that, I pray that you'd help us to be people who are not proud but humbled by this truth.

41:20.128 --> 41:26.535
Maybe we would go out forgiving and bringing your healing of forgiveness to a world that needs.

41:27.536 --> 41:28.618
We pray this in your holy name.

41:28.638 --> 41:28.978
Amen.

